Show Titles recently available

"Signs of Life" = SOL
(a relatively new show which has won several planetarium
and production awards internationally. It talks about
what we're looking for in trying to find life beyond Earth.
It's our highest resolution show.
Click the ink for more information )
This is also the "School Show" for 5th graders who visit
during weekday mornings. (SOL-SS)
 "Water is Life" = WIL

(This is  the "Kiddie show", shown only once at the start of each day.
This is the only show when well-behaved kids under 5 yrs are admitted,
and the show is free for them.)
"Centered in the Universe" = CIU
(The post-renovation premiere show in 2006,
back again because it's always been one of our best.)

currently archived.

My last public show at Griffith Observatory using the old format show --
where we had a specific topic for a few months and could easily add pertinent,
current and correct information to a show "on the fly",
and each show had an extensive, story-telling night sky section,
was on December 30, 2001 at 7:30 pm:
#4679 of a series starting on February 12, 1976.
That last old-format show was "The Christmas Star."

My first public show after becoming a lecturer was a very crowded (about 460 of 635 seats)
Friday night show on February 29, 1976: about Flying Saucers and UFOs.

Lecturers started doing similar current events-based shows
with more audience interaction during the renovation
at the Griffith Observatory Satellite facility near the L.A. Zoo,
from our 69th anniversary (May 14, 2003) to September 3, 2006.
(My last shows at The Satellite were 9/2/06.)

 
If you like statistics, I've been working at Griffith
for 73.32% of my life, including during the renovation and
pandemic closure, when we rehearsed shows by Zoom.
Thatâs 57.93% of the time since Griffith first opened on May 14, 1935!

(I think that the only person who's worked there longer than I have is Dr. Krupp.)

For 94.90% of the time I've worked at Griffith, I've been a Lecturer.
That's 69.58% of my life: well over 2/3rds!
This is over 9000 shows to perhaps as many as 1.3 million people.

February 28, 2024 marked the completion of my 49th year as a lecturer.
(My actual change-in-status from Guide to Lecturer is recorded as 2/29/76 on official City records,
but I was hired after a public show on 2/12/76.)

June 10, 2025 completed my 52nd year of being employed part-time at Griffith Observatory,
starting as a guide in June 1973!

And December 11, 2025 will mark 1.00Â° of Earth's precessional cycle for me,
based on a 25,772 year cycle.
